Now, generally speaking, the Ho Chi Minh Trail, we

00:12.163 --> 00:23.635
got to the point where we operated so much, we 
didn't know just about where it was, but you know,

00:12.163 --> 00:23.635
the Ho Chi Minh Trail was like ants passing through 
your lawn. You stop them up one direction, they

00:24.236 --> 00:29.802
move over a hundred feet and go through the jungle 
and establish another one. Nobody can really

00:31.250 --> 00:42.583
understand this capability of the Viet Cong in 
getting supplies down that Ho Chi Minh Trail from

00:31.250 --> 00:42.583
North Vietnam to South Vietnam until they've 
actually seen it. Then you can understand it. It's

00:44.646 --> 00:50.272
almost unbelievable for me to describe it and for 
you to believe that there's no reason why we

00:44.646 --> 00:50.272
couldn't stop these supplies. But when men have an 
A-frame on their back and will carry

00:55.685 --> 01:04.082
hundred-pound loads on their back and walk 
through the jungle under complete canopy, which

00:55.685 --> 01:04.082
you can't even penetrate with film, then maybe you 
understand. And they walked all the way.

01:07.048 --> 01:09.754
Bicycles, they'd ride bicycles there. If I'm 
getting off the subject. We knew generally where

01:11.678 --> 01:16.528
these routes were, and at night they felt they were 
free to down the usual trail, because nobody could

01:17.015 --> 01:19.198
see them. Well, of course, this stopped when we got 
the gunship capability over there that had the

01:19.238 --> 01:27.147
night vision for the infrared flare, which would 
go by Texas Institute. And again, I was very proud

01:27.167 --> 01:32.694
of getting this introduced into the combat forces 
over there. But there were at times where we knew

01:33.995 --> 01:45.469
there were concentrations of supplies, you know, 
and relays to go from one day and one night, then

01:33.995 --> 01:45.469
stop, then the next night they'd go another maybe 
10 or 12 miles and they'd stop and always move at

01:45.905 --> 02:14.781
night we you know eventually find these 
concentrations and it always turned out that

01:45.905 --> 02:14.781
wherever these concentrations were sure enough 
there'd be some AA defense from them operated by

01:45.905 --> 02:14.781
Pathet Laos now this up down Laos because they knew 
if we found them we're going to hit them well

01:45.905 --> 02:14.781
they're going to start trying to protect them with 
AA and eventually got to be very capable so it built

01:45.905 --> 02:14.781
radar directed AA in Laos This is not very well 
known. But these targets had to be hit, and this was

02:17.503 --> 02:21.767
General Mulmire's responsibility. He had to- one 
of the basic doctors of air force, of course, air

02:21.787 --> 02:31.437
tactics, you've got to hit them in the supply area 
where it hurts the top supply. Interdiction, if

02:31.978 --> 02:33.319
you will. Tactical air warfare. Now, did he have 
authority to hit these targets? Well, he had to

02:38.384 --> 02:45.291
properly identify them and get permission from 
Ambassador Sullivan's to hit these targets.

02:51.052 --> 02:55.418
It required communications that had made things 
more complex and halted. It hindered operations,

02:55.639 --> 02:59.364
but it worked. But when these particular targets 
might, let's say, be near a, let's say, a habitated

03:01.206 --> 03:11.160
center, I call it an inhabited center, a town, if 
you will, in Laos, which, if you bomb there, it

03:11.596 --> 03:15.179
maybe hits civilians. And this is where the 
problems came up. This was forbidden, absolutely

03:16.981 --> 03:20.163
forbidden. You cannot hit certain targets in 
Laos. Well, in warfare, sometimes, you know, it's

03:23.446 --> 03:27.290
difficult. Particularly in the jungle of the 
southeast states, it's hard to identify targets

03:27.450 --> 03:31.553
at best. But sometimes mistakes were made. And 
